The clean web we're building now … Maybe it's like when our parents left cities to build suburbs.
When I browse Facebook and Twitter, I feel sad – we've given up the fun, the play, the creativity, the right.
When I browsed MySpace I felt like I was witnessing the entire globe learning how to make the web at once, together.
We thought MySpace pages looked like shit, but to their creators, they were amazing.
At least then there was massively popular service in which people could be weird, irrational, broken.
We lost something when Facebook won the war vs. MySpace.
Facebook and Twitter represents us like White Pages, through Medium our thoughts read appear as an in-flight magazine.
I mourn for the Internet before it was common for popular services to stamp our identities and content into forms they idealize.
